 Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bereham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Boreham (Essex), Boreham Wood in Elstree (Hertfordshire), Boreham Street in Wartling (Sussex), or Boreham in Warminster (Wiltshire). The placenames in Essex, Sussex and Hertfordshire are probably named with Old English <i>bor</i> ‘hill’ + <i>ham</i> ‘homestead’. Compare   Boram   and   Borom  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Borom","meanings":["English: variant of   Boreham  . Compare   Boram  ."]},{"name":"Boram","meanings":["English (Essex and Kent): variant of   Boreham  . Compare   Borom   and   Borum  ."]},{"name":"Borum","meanings":["Danish: habitational name from any of several places whose name means ‘dwelling place on the edge’.","English (North Yorkshire): variant of   Boreham  . Compare   Boram  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":1,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Bereham II was born in 1258, in Kent, England, his father, Sir Henry de Berham I, was 34 and his mother, Joan de Saxonhurst, was 33. He married Elizabeth Colepepper in 1284, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1289, in Cranbrook, Kent, England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1258–1289":"1258–1289","1259–1288":"1259–1288","1285–1349":"1285–1349","1225–1278":"1225–1278","1226–1265":"1226–1265","1349":"1349","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","1278":"1278","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1265":"1265","24 Jul 1255":"24. juuli 1255","1285":"1285","1284":"1284","Melcombe Regis, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Melcombe Regis, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ardingly, Sussex, England":"Ardingly, Sussex, England","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1258–1289":"1258–1289","1259–1288":"1259–1288","1285–1349":"1285–1349","1225–1278":"1225–1278","1226–1265":"1226–1265","1349":"1349","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","1278":"1278","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1265":"1265","24 Jul 1255":"24. heinäkuuta 1255","1285":"1285","1284":"1284","Melcombe Regis, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Melcombe Regis, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ardingly, Sussex, England":"Ardingly, Sussex, England","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"1258–1289":"1258–1289","1259–1288":"1259–1288","1285–1349":"1285–1349","1225–1278":"1225–1278","1226–1265":"1226–1265","1349":"1349","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","1278":"1278","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1265":"1265","24 Jul 1255":"24 juillet 1255","1285":"12